Practice

Load Datasets

We will work with the largest cities data sets:

cities <- read_csv("../data/largest_cities.csv")
cities

We will also work with the entire U.S. cities data set:

us <- read_csv("../data/us_city_population.csv")
us

Please refer to the previous notebooks for more information about these data sets.

Creating new numeric features

Using the cities data set, create a new feature named city_density by dividing the city population (city_pop) by the city area (city_area). Use the select function to select the city name (name), population, area, and density.

cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area) |>
  select(name, city_pop, city_area, city_density)

The numbers here are very small. What units is the feature city_density currently in? Answer: It is given in millions of people per square kilometer.

Below, modify your code by multiplying the city density by 1000.

cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  select(name, city_pop, city_area, city_density)

Now what are the units of the city density feature? Answer: Thousands of people per square kilometer.

Now, try to summarize the average city density by continent. You should notice that the results include some missing values:

cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  group_by(continent) |>
  summarize(city_density = mean(city_density))

In the code block below, summarize the average city density by continent again but include the parameter na.rm = TRUE in the mean() function.

cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  group_by(continent) |>
  summarize(city_density = mean(city_density, na.rm = TRUE))

Now, below, using the mutate verb, create a plot with city density on the x-axis and metro density on the y-axis. Use a log scale for the axes and include points and text repel labels with the city names.

cities |>
  mutate(city_density = city_pop / city_area * 1000) |>
  mutate(metro_density = metro_pop / metro_area * 1000) |>
  ggplot(aes(city_density, metro_density)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = name)) +
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

What two outliers stick out in this plot? Answer: Guadalajara and Jinan have a much higher metro density than would be expect based on the city density.

Creating new categorical features

Create a bar plot showing the counts of the the koppen_code feature in the cities data set. Order the groups’ categories ordered from the biggest to the smallest. The labels are short so put the categorical variable on the x-axis.

cities |>
  count(koppen_code) |>
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(koppen_code, -n), n)) +
  geom_col()

In the code below, create a new feature called hemisphere which is equal to “North” for cities with a latitude above zero and “South” for cities below zero. Pipe the data to a plot and color the cities by their hemisphere to verify that your code is correct.

cities |>
  mutate(hemisphere = if_else(lat > 0, "North", "South")) |>
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = hemisphere))

Repeat this process below, but this time create a feature called “quadrant” that is equal to “NE”, “NW”, “SE”, and “SE” depending on the sign of the latitude and longitude features. The easiest way to do this is to start by defining a default value and them fill in the quadrants with four uses of the if_else function. Note: use the & operator to combine two conditions (i.e., (lat > 0) & (lon > 0)).

As above, pipe the data into a plot colored by quadrant to verify your work.

cities |>
  mutate(quadrant = "default") |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat > 0) & (lon > 0), "NE", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat > 0) & (lon < 0), "NW", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat < 0) & (lon > 0), "SE", quadrant)) |>
  mutate(quadrant = if_else((lat < 0) & (lon < 0), "SW", quadrant)) |>
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = quadrant))

Grouped Mutate

To conclude, we will apply a few grouped versions of the mutate verb. To make sure we understand how this works, take the us data set, group by city, and compute the maximum value of the population feature for each city.

us |>
  group_by(city) |>
  mutate(population_max = max(population))

Note that this added a new column to a copy of the original data set showing the largest population for each city at any point in time.

Building off of this approach, construct a scatter plot that shows the population of cities in 2010 on the x-axis and the percentage of the 2010 population compared to the maximum population of the city from 1790-2010. Filter to only include cities that are less than 70% of their maximum size in 2010. Use a text repel layer to label each city. (Note: This will require at least two different calls to the mutate function).

us |>
  group_by(city) |>
  mutate(population_max = max(population)) |>
  filter(year == 2010) |>
  mutate(percent_pop_max = population / population_max) |>
  filter(percent_pop_max < 0.7) |>
  ggplot(aes(population, percent_pop_max)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = city))
